observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:
The MAcco to prepare the necessary journal entries to adjust all reconciling items/discrepancies noted herein to accurately present the LGU’s actual cash position for each period;
The MAcco to prepare a year-end adjusting entries to revert the unreleased checks totaling ₱237,614.29 to the CIB account and recognize the corresponding liability/payable account;
The MAcco to provide written explanation on the noted significant variance in the recorded book balance of the CIB-LCCA in the 20% DF and the ending balances in the SCBAA (as well as on the 5% DRRMF), and furnish proofs of reconciliations undertaken together with the MT and MBO;
The MAcco to cause the timely preparation and submission of BRSs; and
The Municipal Treasurer to maintain his cashbook and update and accomplish the certification of transactions at the end of each month as required by the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, and thereafter, reconcile his cash book records with the accounting ledgers.

We recommended the following:
The GSO and/or Inventory Committee to regularly submit the inventory count to be undertaken semestrally, as of June 30 and December 31, and to prepare RPCI and submit the same to the Office of Auditor every July 31 and January 31 each year;
The MAcco and the GSO to prepare and maintain SLCs and SC to account the issuance of its inventories and conduct periodic reconciliation between records, and if with discrepancy, shall be verified and/or adjusted accordingly;
The MDRRMO to regularly submit the inventory of goods and the duly received distribution lists upon released of the relief goods to the GSO;
The GSO to consolidate weekly the Requisition and Issue Slip using the SSMI and submit the same to the MAcco for the computation of the cost of the relief goods issued and draw JEV to recognized expense in the period in which they relate; and
The MAcco to disclose in the Notes to FS the amount of inventories recognized as expense during the audit period.

We recommended the following to Management:
Through the designated HRM Officer, to review and justify the necessity of hiring too many JOs specifically for the positions of Administrative Aide I without classified designation, Administrative Aide I classified as guards, Administrative Aide I classified as utility personnels and Executive Assistants;
Limit hiring of additional JOs and COSs to lower the level of disbursement for their wages considering the previously discussed issues on liquidity risks and in order to maintain a balanced budget;
Prioritize filling up the vacant plantilla positions to reduce heavy reliance on temporary workforce; and
Ensure that hiring of JOs are based on necessity of the Office/Department to avoid waste of government funds.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to make proper disclosures of the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF under the account TL-DRRMF in the Notes to FS in accordance with COA Circular No. 2012-002;
Require the MAcco to verify the discrepancy noted in the Report on Utilization of DRRMF and Status of Implementation of PPAs and make/record the necessary adjustments in conformity to COA Circular 2012-002;
Enjoin the concerned officials to strictly comply with the reportorial requirements laid out in COA Circulars 2012-002 and 2014-002 to have a more reliable and accurate TL-DRRMF account and proper monitoring report for 5% LDRRMF utilization and balances; and
Strictly and prudently comply with all the rules and regulations laid out relative to LDRRMF.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant cause the timely preparation and submission of BRSs as required by COA Circular No. 96-011;
The Municipal Accountant exert earnest efforts in locating the documents and records of prior years, analyze the same to effect necessary adjustments, and come up with a more accurate and reliable financial information;
The Municipal Treasurer prepare and maintain a cashbook and update it regularly as prescribed by the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, and thereafter, reconcile his cash book records with the accounting ledgers;
The Municipal Accountant together with the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Budget Officer (MBO) reconcile their records and the above-noted variances in the 20% DF and 5% LDRRMF appearing in the FS and SCBAA, and thereafter, undertake the same regularly; and
Cash accounts to be monitored by key heads of offices consistently and should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Mayor compel the concerned employees and officials to pay back in full the amounts unduly paid by the LGU for their salary loan amortizations and be reverted back to the funds on which payments were taken;
Only the amounts deducted for salary loan amortizations be remitted by the MTO to the lending institutions, and any late payment of obligations as well as corresponding interest and penalties shall be personally borne by the defaulting employees and officials;
The Municipal Mayor stop the practice of OTC payment and require instead the employees and officials to directly pay outstanding loan obligations to the lending institutions;
Management review the terms and conditions of the Memoranda of Agreement entered by the LGU as collecting agency and the Lending Institutions, and initiate revisions that will accommodate the immediately preceding two (2) recommendations, in favor of the LGU;
The Municipal Mayor along with other concerned employees be vigilant in the granting of additional loans where the employee has no capacity to pay and should give emphasis on the prevention of additional loans which may contravene the GAA provision requiring ₱5,000.00 minimum net take home pay;
All employees and officials update their loan amortizations to make sure that all payments deducted from their salaries have been duly remitted and pay back all payments improperly shouldered by the LGU on their behalf, otherwise a Notice of Disallowance shall be issued; and
The Municipal Mayor assign the preparation of payroll deductions and remittances to the Accounting Office and Treasury Office, respectively, for proper check and balance, as such duties should not be handled by one and the same person or office. We also recommended the Accounting Office to conduct regular reconciliation of salary loan amortization deductions and remittances.

We recommended that:
The LCE and Local Sanggunian formulate clear-cut guidelines on allocations for mobile communications and data services and consider the cheaper and prevailing rates offered by mobile networks and furnish the same guidelines to the Office of the Auditor for reference in audit;
The Municipal Accountant require Certification issued by the agency to which the recipient key personnels were employed to ensure no double claim of similar allowances and said duly signed Certification by their agency head and/or immediate supervisor shall be attached to the payroll for further verification;
Management submit its written justification on the granting of multiple similar allowances in excess of the existing prevailing rates on mobile plans to various employees for further evaluation in audit;
The Municipal Accountant and Property Officer furnish List of Employees issued with Postpaid Plan for Mobile Phone; and
The Municipal Accountant ensure completeness of supporting documents and make certain that for prepaid card users, used cards are surrendered prior to processing and payment of communication allowance to guarantee proper use of government resources.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Mayor, through the concerned office, ensure submission of Memorandum of Agreement and supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor within five working days from perfection thereof, in keeping with COA Circular No. 2009-001;
The Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and implementing departments coordinate and confirm whether projects charged to the above-mentioned fund transfers were actually completed and determine whether there are any other outstanding obligations chargeable to the funds;
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Traesurer determine if the unutilized balances accrue to the National Government Agencies or the LGU in instances of counterpart funds;
If upon verification the projects were completed and no outstanding obligations accrue to the funds, the LGU shall take the following actions:
For funds accruing the NGAs, immediately return the unexpended balances as at year-end to these Source Agencies. If the Source Agency cannot be identified, immediately remit the remaining idle funds to the Bureau of Treasury; and
For counterpart LGU funds, the Local Finance Committee undertake corresponding evaluation and give recommendation on the proper disposition of funds to other priority projects.

We recommended the following:
The end-user or requesting office to obtain certified copies of the (1) page of the approved APP or Supplemental APP, whichever is applicable, and (2) submitted Contract or Purchase Order stamped “Received” by COA to be attached to the Disbursement Voucher;
The BAC Secretariat to submit to the Office of Auditor copies of perfected contracts or Purchase Order along with their required attachments which shall be the basis of issuing a certified copy of the submitted Contract or Purchase Order stamped “Received” by COA;
The BAC Secretariat to issue a stamped certified copy of the page of the approved APP or Supplemental APP to facilitate regularity of all procurements;
The MAcco to require from contractors Progress Billings for progress payments which may serve as a basis for recording transactions to the Construction in Progress account and to effectively execute her pre-audit functions;
The Municipal Mayor as Head of Agency to sign and issue Certificate of Acceptance to signify the acceptance and satisfaction of Management as to the completed projects in behalf of the LGU Dupax del Norte; and
Management and all concerned offices are enjoined to strictly comply to the aforesaid rules and regulations on the documentary requirements and ensure that these are complete and duly attached to the disbursement vouchers to avoid audit suspension, if warranted.

We recommended that:
The MT closely monitor collections from cash tickets to ensure that the same is completely turned-over to the LO, this is also in consideration that cash tickets were not pre-numbered. Additionally, issuances of cash tickets to Collector and every remittance of the same to the LO be properly recorded on a separate logbook to facilitate reconciliation of records;
All the Collectors report and turnover the collections at the close of each business day and accomplish the Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD), and if in case travel time from their places of assignment is more than one day, the turn over shall be made at least once a week or as soon as the collections reach Php5,000.00 in compliance with Section 90, Chapter Three, Book Two of the LTOM, 2nd Edition;
Provide a written explanation of why two copies of the same CTC SN were issued to the designated collector for issuance;
The Collectors and/or LO present and/or submit the duplicate copies or original copies, in case cancelled, of AF Nos. 53 and 54, for audit and verification;
Implement the no erasures and alterations in preparing the OR;
Ensure that all AFs are properly filled-out;
The Collectors attach in the AF No. 51 and RCD upon remittance to the LO the original copy of the Citation Tickets issued to Violators and surrendered by them;
The AF Custodian and Collector concerned to properly account in the permanent logbook the issued Citation Tickets to the PNP and the original copy surrendered by the Violator for additional control; and
Management strictly comply with all the rules and regulations prescribed under Chapter III, Book 2 of the LTOM 2nd Edition and Revised Cash Examination Manual.

We recommended to Management the following:

the Municipal Mayor, together with the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council (MDRRMC), through the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO), judicially plan the utilization of the LDRRMF focusing on PPAs requiring the highest priority in terms of urgency and/or impact on the four thematic areas of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management;

the MDRRMO include in the subsequent Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) only those that can be implemented during the year through efficient planning and procurement activities;

the MDRRMO, in a separate caption, include in the subsequent LDRRMFIP and in the revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) the savings accounted totaling to P206,704.66, along with any additional savings from all completed projects, for its appropriate release and utilization; and

the MDRRMO, together with the Municipal Engineer and in cooperation with the heads of other offices concerned, expedite and ensure the full implementation of all identified priority PPAs to optimize the utilization of the 5% LDRRMF.

The Audit Team recommended the following: 

The BAC prepare a resolution delegating to specific officials, personnel or committee or office the conduct of Direct Retail Purchase of POL. Likewise, the Municipal Mayor shall prepare and issue an order for the purpose;

Since the Municipal Mayor is the delegating authority for the direct retail purchase, each office should estimate its necessary POL requirements within the fiscal year, including provisions for foreseeable emergencies based on historical records, which will be subjected to direct retail purchase. Moreover, consolidate such in the Annual Procurement Plan of the Mayor’s Office, in its entirety, including any amendment thereto which shall be reflected in the supplemental APP;

The Municipal Mayor, being the Head of the Procuring Entity, duly execute and approve a contract or purchase order for all direct retail purchase of POL; 

The direct purchase must be made from retailers or dealers identified to be capable of delivering the required POL products at the most reasonable retail price; and

The Management should strictly comply with the provisions of Revenue Memorandum Order No. 23-2014 on the withholding of taxes to avoid legal action from the Bureau of Internal Revenue against the erring withholding agents.

The Audit Team recommended:

The Municipal Treasury Office to collect the appropriate fees imposed by local ordinances;

The Sangguniang Bayan Office to consider revising or amending the contents of Comprehensive Solid Waste Management Code to reflect the appropriate amount of fees to be imposed;

The Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Office to coordinate with the barangays serviced by its waste collectors to determine the proper agency which should impose the fees from households.

We recommended management to:

1. Require the Department Heads/Division Chiefs and heads of other end-user units to submit to the BAC Secretariat their duly approved Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMPs) for their different programs, activities and projects during the year and ensure that pertinent information/data as provided under Sec. 7.3 of the IRR of RA 9184 are included therein;

2. Require the BAC Secretariat to consolidate the submitted PPMPs into an Annual Procurement Plan (APP) and to prepare the required APP for common-use supplies and equipment for submission to DBM using the standard form as set forth by the regulation;

3. Require the concerned Department Heads/Division Chiefs and heads of other end-user units to update their PPMPs every six (6) months or whenever necessary and for the BAC Secretariat to consolidate the updated PPMPs in the original APP.
